passages.text: US consumer credit continued to exhibit improving trends in July despite ongoing macro uncertainty. Non- mortgage delinquencies declined across multiple categories, with \(60+\) day card delinquencies down 15 bps y/y to \(2.76\%\) and personal loan delinquencies down 27 bps to \(3.25\%\) , mitigated by auto loan delinquencies rising 2 bps to \(1.51\%\) in July. Delinquency trends have been broadly declining y/y for cards since January 2025 and personal loans since November 2024, with auto loan delinquencies flat- to- up y/y over the past six months. Meanwhile, new account originations were flat y/y for cards, down modestly for autos after tariff- related pull- forward activity earlier this year and up double- digits for personal loans driven by fintech activity. We favor Buy- rated Fair Isaac for its wide competitive moat and pricing power in the Scores business, which we believe remain intact even after the FHFAs lender choice decision, and for its idiosyncratic platform transformation in the Software business. We stay Neutral- rated on Equifax given state budget, white collar staffing and criminal background screening share shift headwinds in the EWS business, and are sidelined on TransUnion, in the context of lending volumes coming below historical averages among the company's fintech and small & regional bank customers.

Delinquencies continuing to show signs of improvement. Delinquency rates, which serve as one of the most reliable indicators of consumer credit health, continued to show signs of improvement in July for most non- mortgage categories. The \(60+\) day bankcard delinquency rate moved lower y/y to \(2.76\%\) in July from \(2.91\%\) , though remains above the long- term average of \(2.47\%\) since 2009. Meanwhile, the \(60+\) day personal loan delinquency rate declined y/y to \(3.25\%\) in July from \(3.52\%\) , and comes below the long- term average of \(3.79\%\) since 2009. The \(60+\) day auto loan delinquency rate ticked slightly higher y/y to \(1.51\%\) in July from \(1.49\%\) , and comes over one standard deviation above the long- term average of \(0.98\%\) since 2009. In the month of July, the second derivative of y/y change in delinquency rates improved for cards, personal loans and autos. Declining delinquencies typically cause banks to loosen their underwriting standards, which benefits credit origination volumes.

Mortgage delinquencies remain low. In contrast to card and auto delinquency rates, which are currently above their respective long- term averages, mortgage delinquencies remain benign and well below their historical average, reflecting banks' tight mortgage underwriting standards over a decade after the Global Financial Crisis. The \(90+\) day mortgage delinquency rate of \(0.71\%\) in July increased y/y from \(0.54\%\) , but remains well below the long- term average of \(2.58\%\) since 2009. While low mortgage delinquencies point to a low likelihood of a wave of defaults, high mortgage rates, low housing inventory and elevated home prices continue to weigh on mortgage origination volumes.

Consumer credit drivers generally favorable. Broader drivers of consumer credit Health are generally favorable. The US unemployment rate of \(4.2\%\) in July ticked higher from \(4.1\%\) in June and comes below the long- term average of \(5.7\%\) since 1991. Additionally, real wage growth is positive, registering \(1.2\%\) in July, pointing to increased real spending power. Household debt as a \(\%\) of nominal GDP of \(60.6\%\) through 2Q comes below the \(70.0\%\) average since 2003, and debt service payments as a \(\%\) of disposable income of \(11.2\%\) through 2Q compares favorably to the \(12.5\%\) average since 1998. That said, personal savings as a \(\%\) of disposable income of \(4.5\%\) in June falls below the long- term average of \(5.6\%\) since 1998.

Mortgage account originations up y/y. Mortgage account originations increased \(9.3\%\) y/y in May (latest data available), decelerating from \(12.8\%\) in April, and compares to full year growth of \(8.6\%\) in 2024 and \(22.4\%\) in 2025 as estimated by the Mortgage Bankers Association. The 30- year mortgage rate registered \(6.6\%\) as of 8/28, compared to a high of nearly \(8\%\) in early November 2023 and a low of \(2.7\%\) in early 2021. Median blended new and existing home prices declined \(0.7\%\) y/y in July, the first monthly y/y decline in two years. Total mortgage debt outstanding increased \(3.6\%\) y/y in July to \$12.7tn. The \(90+\) day delinquency rate for mortgages of \(0.71\%\) in July increased y/y from \(0.54\%\) , but compares favorably to the long- term average of \(2.58\%\) since 2009.

Card originations down slightly. Credit card account originations have been in a broad- based decline since September 2022 as banks tightened lending standards in response to macro uncertainty. Card account originations inclusive of bancards and private labels decreased \(0.7\%\) y/y in May (latest data available), improving from a \(1.1\%\) decline in April, with overall prime originations down \(3.7\%\) and overall subprime originations up \(13.7\%\) . Total credit card balances outstanding increased \(3.4\%\) y/y in July to \(\) 1.1\(tn. The 60+ day delinquency rate for bancards of 2.76\% in July declined y/y from 2.91\%, but comes above the long - term average of 2.47\% since 2009. Credit card write - offs of 0.59\% in July declined y/y from 0.60\%, but come above the long - term average of 0.46\% since 2009.

Personal loan originations sustaining growth. Personal loan account originations were up \(11.5\%\) y/y in May (latest data available), consistent with \(11.6\%\) growth in April, with prime originations up \(6.1\%\) and subprime originations up \(22.5\%\) . Account originations for personal loans had been in y/y decline in nearly all months between September 2022 and January 2025 as banks pulled back on risky unsecured lending, particularly in the subprime category, but have now registered four consecutive months of y/y growth. Total personal loans outstanding increased \(2.2\%\) y/y in July 2025 to \(\) 149bn\(. The\) 60+ day delinquency rate for personal loans of\) 3.25\% \(in July decreased y/y from\) 3.52\% \(, and comes below the long - term average of\) 3.79\% \(since 2009. Personal loan write - offs of\) 0.73\% \(in July decreased y/y from\) 0.85\% \(, but come above the long - term average of\) 0.63\% \(since 2009.

Auto loan originations normalize. Auto loan account originations decreased \(3.5\%\) y/y in May (latest data available), worsening from \(2.7\%\) growth in April, with prime originations down \(4.4\%\) and subprime originations up \(1.4\%\) . Account originations had declined consistently between March 2022 and November 2023, and fluctuated between growth and decline over the course of 2024 and 2025. Auto loan account originations earlier in 2025 included a tariff- related pull- forward of auto purchases, suggesting future origination growth may moderate. Total auto loans outstanding increased \(1.5\%\) y/y in July to \(\) 1.7\mathrm{tn}\(The\) 60+ day delinquency rate for auto loans ticked higher y/y to \(1.51\%\) in July from \(1.49\%\) , and comes over one standard deviation above the long- term average of \(0.98\%\) since 2009. Auto loan write- offs declined slightly y/y to \(0.23\%\) in July from \(0.24\%\) , and come in- line with the long- term average since 2009.

Against a backdrop of consumer credit delinquencies that remain above long- term averages, subdued consumer credit volumes and declining consumer confidence, we favor business models among the credit bureaus with the following characteristics: 1) pricing power, 2) monopoly or near- monopoly market structure, 3) recurring revenue streams, 4) track record of beat- and- raise results even against a volatile macro backdrop, 5) idiosyncratic catalysts and 6) superior margin flow- through. We believe Buy- rated FICO satisfies these criteria.

Fair Isaac (FICO, Buy, \(1,915 12M PT\) ): FICO is continuing to realize robust mortgage score pricing increases that drove the significant majority of the \(34\%\) y/y Scores revenue growth in F3Q, with mortgage revenue up a robust \(53\%\) . The company is also passing through accelerated double- digit auto score pricing increases that we believe can be sustained over time. Despite the FHFAs recent lender choice announcement for mortgage scores, FICO expects lenders to continue to rely on Classic FICO and, increasingly, FICO 10T scores, with no lenders switching to VantageScore since the FHFAs decision, and importantly noted that its original mortgage score pricing strategy has not changed. The company is also delivering accelerating Software platform ARR growth in the high- teens, with a path to return to \(\sim 30\%\) growth over the long term. We believe FICO can continue to deliver mid- teens revenue growth and \(20\% +\) EPS growth supported by the company's ongoing ability to close the price- to- value gap in its Scores business and idiosyncratic platform transformation in its Software business. The sell- off in FICO shares following FHFA developments presents an attractive buying opportunity, particularly given the company's economics remain intact, in our view.

Equifax (EFX, Neutral, \(\) 253 12M PT\(): Equifax is continuing to see a stable lending environment despite macro uncertainty, with B2B non - mortgage revenue up\) 4\% \(y/y in 2Q, albeit at levels below historical norms. Mortgage revenue also increased a robust\) 20\% \(y/y in the quarter, driving the majority of the revenue upside, reflecting strength from pricing flow - through from FICO and mortgage pre - approval & pre - qualification solutions, the latter of which should benefit in 2H from integration with the TWN indicator product at no additional cost to customers. That said, we expect EWS revenue performance in the second half of the year to be dampened by funding pressures among state agencies given reduced federal reimbursements, weak talent solutions and employer services trends in the context of soft white collar hiring volumes, and recent share loss in criminal background screening. We also have a more conservative EBITDA margin outlook due to higher litigation expenses, and now expect flat margins on a full year basis.

TransUnion (TRU, Neutral, \(\) 102 12M PT\(): Despite an uncertain macro environment, TransUnion is seeing stable lending volumes and consumer financial health. In 2Q, credit card volumes were flat y/y, auto loan volumes were up low - single - digits lifted by April tariff - related pull - forward purchase activity and consumer lending volumes were up mid - teens. Mortgage credit inquiries were also flat y/y, though mortgage revenue representing\) 12\% \(of LTM revenue rose a robust\) 29\% \(on FICO pricing increases. The

company now expects full- year organic constant currency revenue growth of \(6 - 7\%\) , up from \(4.5 - 6\%\) previously, and noted that a continuation of July credit trends could land revenue at or above the upper end of the guidance range. That said, TRU's margin outlook for in the back half of the year is challenged, with EBITDA margins contracting 40 bps and 120 bps y/y based on guidance due to M&A margin dilution, investment activity, fewer productivity benefits and revenue mix.

Fair Isaac (FICO): We are Buy- rated on FICO. Our 12- month price target of \(\) 1,915\(is based on 48.0x our NTM + 1 YR EPS estimate of\) \ \(39.89\) . Our target multiple comes at a premium to the Info Services peer group median of \(28.0x\) to reflect FICO's strong pricing power in the Scores business and attractive long- term earnings potential from its transformation into a decision management software provider. Key risks include a lack of traction with FICO's decision management software transformation, an inability to sustain elevated pricing increases in the Scores business, a macro and credit market downturn, and competitive threats.

Equifax (EFX): We are Neutral- rated on EFX. Our 12- month price of \(\) 253\(is based on 25.0x our NTM + 1 YR EPS estimate of\) \ \(10.14\) . Our target multiple comes at a discount to the Info Services peer group median of \(28.0x\) in the context of EFX's higher transaction revenue mix and ongoing subprime consumer credit headwinds. Key risks to the downside for EFX shares include macro and interest rate risk, subprime consumer credit origination headwinds, and mortgage origination volume volatility. Key risks to the upside include a rebound in mortgage origination volumes, expansion in non- mortgage credit inquiries, rapid product introductions, further adoption of EWS offerings and healthy international expansion.

TransUnion (TRU): We are Neutral- rated on TRU. We lower our 12- month price target from \(\) 102\(to\) \ \(96\) based on \(18.0x\) (19.0x prior) our NTM + 1 YR EPS estimate of \(\) 5.35\(unchanged). We trim our target multiple to reflect ongoing macro uncertainty that poses greater risk to subprime and fintech customers. Our target multiple comes at a discount to the Info Services peer group median of \(28.0x\) to reflect TRU's higher mix of macro sensitive transaction revenues, and exposure to the fintech and subprime categories. Key risks to the downside include a macro and credit market downturn, mortgage origination volume declines, growth and margin dilution from M&A, FX headwinds and financial leverage. Key risks to the upside include a strengthening economic backdrop, healthy growth in international and emerging markets, traction in US emerging verticals and increasing revenue contributions from income and employment verification.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
